    <p>A Steve Jobs presentation is strikingly simple, visual, and devoid of bullet points. Thatâ€™s rightâ€”no bullet points. Ever. Of course, this raises the question, would a PowerPoint presentation without bullets still be a PowerPoint presentation? The answer is yes, and a much more interesting one. New research into cognitive functioningâ€”how the brain worksâ€”proves that bullet points are the least effective way to deliver important information. Neuroscientists are finding that what passes as a typical presentation is usually the worst way to engage your audience.</p>
